3. JWT role changes aren't immediate
Auth.js uses JWT-only sessions (no DB sessions). If you change a user's role from user to admin (or revoke admin), the change won't take effect until their JWT expires. Depending on session maxAge, that could be hours or days.
Not a current concern (no plans to add admins). Becomes relevant when Stripe (phase 2) introduces paid/free tiers — a user upgrading to pro expects new features immediately after payment.
Recommended approach (Option C): do not store plan/tier in the JWT. After Stripe webhook confirms payment and updates the DB, feature-gated pages/routes do a lightweight DB check (SELECT plan FROM users WHERE id = ?) only on screens that require it. Avoids JWT complexity and keeps extra DB queries scoped to gated routes only — acceptable given connection_limit=10.

4. ~~Rating ELO is global, not per-tournament~~ ✓ BY DESIGN — The app is a personal/social intelligence tool, not a tournament management system. Global ELO across all matches is intentional. For formal tournament ratings, players rely on DUPR.




